I see that you have implemented most of the functionalities required in the assignment. However, as you mentioned, you are missing the Add, Edit, and Delete functionalities in the AdminDashboard form as well as the ability for the admin to edit the customer database. Here's how you can implement these features:

1. First, you need to load the data from your Access database to your Data Grid View in the AdminDashboard form. Add the following code to the `AdminDashboardForm_Load` event in the AdminDashboardForm.cs:

```csharp
using System.Data.OleDb;

OleDbConnection con = new OleDbConnection("Provider=Microsoft.Jet.OLEDB.4.0;Data Source=db_users.mdb");
OleDbCommand cmd = new OleDbCommand();
OleDbDataAdapter da = new OleDbDataAdapter();
DataSet ds = new DataSet();

private void AdminDashboardForm_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    con.Open();
    string query = "SELECT * FROM ApplianceDBLIST"; // Assuming your appliance table name is ApplianceDBLIST
    cmd = new OleDbCommand(query, con);
    da.SelectCommand = cmd;
    da.Fill(ds, "ApplianceDBLIST");
    dataGridView1.DataSource = ds.Tables["ApplianceDBLIST"].DefaultView;
    con.Close();
}
```

2. Now, let's implement the Add functionality. Add the following code to the `Add_Click` event in the AdminDashboardForm.cs:

```csharp
private void Add_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    // Create a form for adding new appliances, and show it as a dialog
    AddApplianceForm addApplianceForm = new AddApplianceForm();
    if (addApplianceForm.ShowDialog() == DialogResult.OK)
    {
        AdminDashboardForm_Load(sender, e); // Refresh the data grid view
    }
}
```

You will also need to create the AddApplianceForm form and handle the appliance addition logic in that form.

3. Similarly, implement the Edit functionality by adding the following code to the `Edit_Click` event in the AdminDashboardForm.cs:

```csharp
private void Edit_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (dataGridView1.SelectedRows.Count > 0)
    {
        // Assuming you have an "ID" column in your appliance table as a primary key
        string selectedId = dataGridView1.SelectedRows[0].Cells["ID"].Value.ToString();

        // Create an edit form and pass the selected appliance ID
        EditApplianceForm editApplianceForm = new EditApplianceForm(selectedId);
        if (editApplianceForm.ShowDialog() == DialogResult.OK)
        {
            AdminDashboardForm_Load(sender, e); // Refresh the data grid view
        }
    }
    else
    {
        MessageBox.Show("Please select a row to edit.");
    }
}
```

Again, create an EditApplianceForm form and handle the appliance editing logic in that form.

4. And finally, implement the Delete functionality by adding the following code to the `Delete_Click` event in the AdminDashboardForm.cs:

```csharp
private void Delete_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    if (dataGridView1.SelectedRows.Count > 0)
    {
        string selectedId = dataGridView1.SelectedRows[0].Cells["ID"].Value.ToString();

        con.Open();
        string deleteQuery = "DELETE FROM ApplianceDBLIST WHERE ID=" + selectedId; // Assuming you have an "ID" column in your appliance table as a primary key
        cmd = new OleDbCommand(deleteQuery, con);
        cmd.ExecuteNonQuery();
        con.Close();

        AdminDashboardForm_Load(sender, e); // Refresh the data grid view
    }
    else
    {
        MessageBox.Show("Please select a row to delete.");
    }
}
```

5. To allow the admin to edit the customer database, create another Data Grid View in the AdminDashboardForm and load the customer data into it following the same steps as in point 1. Then, create Add, Edit, and Delete buttons for the customer data and implement the logic in a similar way to points 2-4.

After completing the above steps, your AdminDashboard should have the functionalities for adding, editing, and deleting appliance and customer data. Make sure to refactor the code and implement the necessary error handling as needed.

Certainly! Since you have already connected the DataGridView to the database manually and enabled the editing, adding, and deleting features, you do not need to create separate forms for these actions. In this case, you can use DataGridView's built-in functionalities to manipulate the data directly. 

Follow these steps to implement the Add, Edit, and Delete functionalities using the DataGridView's built-in features:

1. Remove the current Add, Edit, and Delete buttons in the AdminDashboard form as you will be using DataGridView's built-in functionalities.

2. When DataGridView is connected to the database, enabling the "Enable Adding", "Enable Editing", and "Enable Deleting" options should automatically handle these functionalities. Users can directly click on the DataGridView cells, edit the values, and changes will be persisted in the database when the cell is no longer in edit mode.

To ensure that the DataGridView's DataSource is set up correctly, create a `BindingSource`, fill it, and set it to the DataGridView's DataSource:

```csharp
BindingSource bindingSource = new BindingSource();

private void AdminDashboardForm_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    con.Open();
    string query = "SELECT * FROM ApplianceDBLIST"; // Assuming your appliance table name is ApplianceDBLIST
    cmd = new OleDbCommand(query, con);
    da.SelectCommand = cmd;
    da.Fill(ds, "ApplianceDBLIST");
    bindingSource.DataSource = ds.Tables["ApplianceDBLIST"].DefaultView;
    dataGridView1.DataSource = bindingSource;
    con.Close();
}
```

3. Add an event that listens for any data change in the DataGridView, and updates the database accordingly. You can use the `CellEndEdit` event:

```csharp
private void dataGridView1_CellEndEdit(object sender, DataGridViewCellEventArgs e)
{
    con.Open();
    da.Update(ds, "ApplianceDBLIST");
    con.Close();
}
```

4. Implement a similar workflow for managing the customer database. Add another DataGridView to display the customer data, and enable the "Enable Adding", "Enable Editing", and "Enable Deleting" options. Then, set up the DataSource and event handling just as you did for the appliance data.

Now, your AdminDashboard form should allow you to add, edit, and delete appliance and customer data directly in the DataGridView.

Remember to add error handling and ensure you're meeting all other requirements of the assignment.

I apologize for the confusion. It appears that the DataGridView is not committing the changes to the database. You need to add some more code in the `CellEndEdit` event to save the changes properly.

First, update the `AdminDashboardForm_Load` method to include a new `OleDbCommandBuilder` which generates the necessary SQL commands to update the data source:

```csharp
OleDbCommandBuilder commandBuilder;

private void AdminDashboardForm_Load(object sender, EventArgs e)
{
    con.Open();
    string query = "SELECT * FROM ApplianceDBLIST"; // Assuming your appliance table name is ApplianceDBLIST
    cmd = new OleDbCommand(query, con);
    da.SelectCommand = cmd;
    commandBuilder = new OleDbCommandBuilder(da); // Add this line
    da.Fill(ds, "ApplianceDBLIST");
    bindingSource.DataSource = ds.Tables["ApplianceDBLIST"].DefaultView;
    dataGridView1.DataSource = bindingSource;
    con.Close();
}
```

Now update the `dataGridView1_CellEndEdit` event:

```csharp
private void dataGridView1_CellEndEdit(object sender, DataGridViewCellEventArgs e)
{
    con.Open();
    da.Update(ds, "ApplianceDBLIST");
    con.Close();
    ds.Tables["ApplianceDBLIST"].AcceptChanges(); // Add this line
}
```

Do the same for the customer data DataGridView.

This should save the changes to the database when you edit the cells in the DataGridView. Make sure to handle errors properly and close the database connection using `con.Close()` in a `finally` block.

